        "author_association": "MEMBER",
        "body": "One can do FFTs on the chunks and them combine them (Cooley-Tukey-like) with the \"butterfly\" operator (with twiddle factors, etc.), which is many-to-many; you would presumably need N=2**x where N is the number of chunks on the dimension and x is the number of shuffles/generations. This works particularly well when you can write the data back to the same allocated array space, but in our case probably means temporarily at least doubling memory use within a generation.\r\nWhen I looked into this some time ago, \r\nI found the following two old papers that might be useful:\r\n- C Calvin, 1996, Implementation of parallel FFT algorithms on distributed memory machines with a minimum overhead of communication.\r\n- T H Cormen, 1997, Determining an Out-ofcore FFT Decomposition Strategy for Parallel Disks by Dynamic Programming",
        "reactions": {
