        "author_association": "NONE",
        "body": "@grlee77 I didn't even remember I had that repo, and I can't say anything about whether the code in there works.  In particular, I've never been very good at using dask, so I kind of think I just gave up on that repo.\r\n\r\nHowever, I have https://github.com/moble/out_of_core_fft, which was mostly written after that other repo.  I can't guarantee its current state (e.g., CI fails because of pytest updates), but I will say that it has worked very well for me and others in the past, even for FFTs of arrays of sizes upwards of 32GB (which was ~4 times as big as my total memory at the time).\r\n\r\nI should note that, because of the nature of this approach, there is potential for this to be *extremely* slow if memory-access patterns get weird.  I guess a dask chunk has similar issues to HDF5 chunks \u2014 which is what I was dealing with in that second repo.  But there are almost certainly use cases I didn't consider, so it would probably pay to put some thought into generalizing my approach.\r\n\r\nBut if some dask expert could push this through, I think it would be a really cool addition!",
